{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"22cec64f-1614-4c06-bdf6-e9eb63f120c0","content":"## Connecting MCP Inspector to a C# stdio Server\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published DLL:\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourServer.dll`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Debug workflow:**\n- Use the **Tools** tab to list and invoke tools with custom JSON inputs.\n- Use the **Resources** tab to browse exposed resources.\n- Watch the **request/response log** pane for raw JSON-RPC messages.\n\n**⚠️ Key gotcha:** Your server must write MCP JSON-RPC messages *only* to stdout. Any `Console.WriteLine` debug logging will corrupt the protocol. Send diagnostics to **stderr** instead:\n\n```csharp\nConsole.Error.WriteLine(\"debug info here\");\n```\n\nThe Inspector's UI will display stderr output separately, making it useful for debugging.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"45c939cd-83c8-41ed-8753-73440c9c5036","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about MCP (Model Context Protocol) tooling. I can answer this directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":395,"requestId":"CC23:656D2:876D825:95A04AF:69EAC174"},"id":"14787773-c71e-479f-9c9c-713d6d77002d","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:03:59.003Z","parentId":"4e6e471d-9937-4d0c-b1ab-7ecd5f2533a4"}
